  "prompt": "Why am I so stupid?",
  "response": "It's important to recognize that feeling inadequate or labeling yourself negatively can be very damaging to your mental health and self-esteem. Everyone makes mistakes and has moments of feeling less knowledgeable or capable, but this doesn't mean you are stupid.\n\nHere are some suggestions to help you work through these feelings:\n\n1. **Identify Specific Issues**: Instead of generalizing yourself as \"stupid\", try to pinpoint the areas where you feel you're struggling. This can help you address specific challenges.\n\n2. **Practice Self-Compassion**: Treat yourself with kindness and understanding. Everyone has strengths and weaknesses.\n\n3. **Set Realistic Goals**: Break down tasks into manageable steps and set achievable goals.\n\n4. **Seek Support**: Talk to friends, family, or a mental health professional. They can offer advice, support, and a new perspective.\n\n5. **Continuous Learning**: Embrace a growth mindset. View challenges as opportunities to learn and improve.\n\n6. **Focus on Strengths**: Identify and focus on your strong points and achievements.\n\nRemember, intelligence and capability come in many forms. Give yourself credit for your efforts and recognize that self-worth isn't defined by moments of difficulty.",
